\begin_layout Standard

For all 
\begin_inset Formula $x_k$
\end_inset

, by the mean value theorem, there is a value 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_k$
\end_inset

 that satisfies the following: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
	g^\prime(\theta_k) = \frac{g(x_k) - g(x^\star)}{x_k - x^\star}
\end{align}
\end_inset

and, as the book elaborates, this is equivalent to: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
	(x_k - x^\star)g^\prime(\theta_k) &= g(x_k) - g(x^\star) \\
	e_{k+1} &= g^\prime(\theta_k)e_k
\end{align}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

By examining equation (1), it becomes obvious that, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
	\lim\limits_{k \rightarrow \infty} \frac{g(x_k) - g(x^\star)}{x_k - x^\star} = g^\prime(x^\star)
\end{align}
\end_inset

due to the definition of the derivative, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x_k)$
\end_inset

 converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $x^\star$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

From this, we can see:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
	\lim\limits_{k \rightarrow \infty} \frac{|e_{k+1}|}{|e_k|} &= \lim\limits_{k \rightarrow \infty} \frac{|g(\theta_k)||e_k|}{|e_k|} \\
															   &= \lim\limits_{k \rightarrow \infty} |g(\theta_k)|		
\end{align}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Therefore, by combining the results of equations (1) and (4), it follows that: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
	\lim\limits_{k \rightarrow \infty} \frac{|e_{k+1}|}{|e_k|} = g^\prime(x^\star)
\end{align}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Now, for this question, we are considering the case of when 
\begin_inset Formula $g^\prime(x^\star)$
\end_inset

 happens to be zero. So, to start with this, let's express the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x_k)$
\end_inset

 as a Taylor series (this part was omitted in the book, much to my ire): 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
	g(x_k) = g(x^\star) + g^\prime(x^\star)(x_k - x^\star) + \frac{g^{\prime\prime}(\xi_k)}{2}(x_k - x^\star)^2
\end{align}
\end_inset

By Taylor's theorem, using the explicit formula for the remainder, this result is exact for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_k$
\end_inset

. Since we are interested only when 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x^\star) = 0$
\end_inset

, we can simplify the previous equation: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
	g(x_k) = g(x^\star) + \frac{g^{\prime\prime}(\xi_k)}{2}(x_k - x^\star)^2
\end{align}
\end_inset

From this, remembering that 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{k + 1} = g(x_k) - x^\star = g(x_k) - g(x^\star)$
\end_inset

, we can conclude: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
	e_{k + 1} &= \frac{g^{\prime\prime}(\xi_k)}{2}(x_k - x^\star)^2 \\
			  &= \frac{g^{\prime\prime}(\xi_k)}{2}(e_k)^2
\end{align}
\end_inset

Also, using the same logic as in equation (4): 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
		\lim\limits_{k \rightarrow \infty} \frac{g(x_k) - g(x^\star)}{(x_k - x^\star)^2} = \frac{g^{\prime\prime}(x^\star)}{2}
\end{align}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

